@NODE Introduction "Introduction"
@TOC Main
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}Introduction@{ub}



Universal Translator is a program that will convert catalog description
files into source code for a program's internal strings, or to an external
catalog file for other languages.


There are several other programs that do this, also.  They all have their
own special features and way of handling catalog description and catalog
translation files.  Universal Translator has taken the best features of each
program and made them better.  It also hase some features unique to Universal
Translator.


Universal Translator also handles catalogs in a much more efficient and
convenient manner.  Only one file is required, not two, like other programs
require.


All other comparible catalog description converter programs require the
user to maintain @{b}two@{ub} files for @{b}one@{ub} catalog.  They require a
catalog description file, ex. program.cd, and a catalog translation file,
ex. program.ct.


To make an external catalog with some other program, such as CatComp, the
programmer has to release a catalog translation file with blank lines for the
person to translate the strings.  The translator then sends it back to the
program's author who converts it to a catalog description file, hoping the
translator got all his needed preferences correct.  He then converts it to an
external catalog file.


This sequence takes two more steps than Universal Translator and has no
guarantee that the strings will be the correct length since catalog translation
files have no preferences in them.  If the string is too short or long, and the
programmer doesn't know the language, he would have to send it back, or just
send an e-mail message, to the translator to get it adjusted.  This could take
several days.


Universal Translator only requires @{b}one@{ub} file, a catalog description file.


To make an external catalog using Universal Translator works much the same.
The programmer releases a blank catalog @{b}description@{ub} file with blank
lines for the translated strings.


The difference here is that all the programmer's preferences for each
string is included, so the translator will get the string correct the first
time.  The strings are also laid out the way they will be seen in the program,
as in all linefeeds will start a new line, instead of having one long line
that could easily be mis-translated.


The translator returns the catalog description file to the programmer and
he converts it directly to an external catalog, or even source code for
internal strings.


Using Universal Translator requires only one file, the blank catalog
description file, which will be translated more accurately, makes less work
for the programmer, supports all popular programming languages, and countless
other minor, but important, aspects will be handled correctly.


