@NODE CreatingCDF "Creating A Catalog Description File"
@TOC UsingProgram
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}Creating A Catalog Description File@{ub}



Creating a catalog description file is quite simple.  The file consists of

only two sections: the header and the body of strings.  It is best to group

strings according to their source code module, not just thrown in at the end of

the file.  Keeping them organized into groups and in sequence with the source

code will make updating the strings much easier.



The header consists of the three lines:


## version $VER: program.catalog version (date) comment

## language xxxxx

## codeset 0


example:


## version $VER: universaltranslator.catalog 15.2 (20.07.94) Internal strings

## language english

## codeset 0


The entire version line must be only one line, 256 characters.

Set codeset to 0, it is unused at this time.



The body of the catalog description file is where all the work is

accomplished.  For each string, there must be: an indentifier, a preferences

structure, and the string itself.


All identifiers must be all capitals and begin with: MSG_.  Every string

must have a preferences structure: (//).


MSG_LIBS_COULD_NOT_OPEN_INTUITION_LIBRARY (1//)

Could not open Intuition library.

MSG_LIBS_COULD_NOT_OPEN_GRAPHICS_LIBRARY (//)

Could not open Graphics library.


It is best to make the identifier the same as the string for easy

identification.


The prefences structure consists of three flags: (string number/minimum

characters/maximum characters).  A string number doesn't have to be given for

every string, they will automatically be numbered and changed only when

specified then numbered automatically after the new number.  The minimum and

maximum characters should not be used very often.  The user interface should

adjust to the strings, not the strings to the user interface.


;

; *** AmigaGuide.c ***

;

MSG_SELECT_AMIGAGUIDE_HELP_FILE (//100)

Select AmigaGuide help file

;

; *** Aux.c ***

;

MSG_MY_EASY_REQUEST_TITLE (//)

%s Request

;

; *** Asl_GetFile.c ***

;

MSG_ASL_SAVE (//)

Save

MSG_ASL_OPEN (//)

Open

MSG_ASL_FILE_ALREADY_EXISTS_REPLACE_IT (//)

\\"%s\\"\\

\\nalready exists.  Replace it?


A semi-colon as the first character designates a comment.


Keeping the strings grouped by subject will make updating easier.


MSG_ABOUT_TEXT (//)

%s\\n\\

By: %s\\n\\n\\

Version: %s     Released: %s\\n\\n\\

Copyright © 1993-1994   All Rights Reserved


The above lines are all for one string.  At the end of each line there is a

backslash, \\, to indicate that there is more data for this string.  By

splitting the string into multiple lines, just like it will be displayed on

screen, will make it much easier to read and translate.


The following is a list of backslash control sequences accepted by

Universal Translator and other program:


  \\0    NULL

  \\a    Display beep

  \\b    Backspace

  \\t    Tab

  \\n    Line feed

  \\v    Vertical tab

  \\f    Form feed

  \\r    Carriage return

  \\e    Escape

  \\c    Control sequence introducer

  \\\\    The backslash itself

  \\"    Quote

  \\xHH  ASCII code HH (Where HH are hex digits 0-9, A-F)

  \\###  ASCII code ### (Where ### are octal digits 0-7)


When counting characters for either a minumum or maximum number, each one

of these counts as one character except \\xHH which counts as two.


@ENDNODE


@NODE ConvertingBlankCDF "Converting A Blank Catalog Description File"
@TOC UsingProgram
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}Converting A Blank Catalog Description File@{ub}



Converting a blank catalog description file is very simple, you just fill

in the blanks, literally.


Fill in the header with your name as the translator, the date, and to which

language you translated the strings to.  Do not change anything else.


## version $VER: universaltranslator.catalog 15.2 (20.07.94) Translated by: [Your Name]

## language xxxxxxx

## codeset 0


The strings are laid out just like the programmer did in the original

description file.  All the comments are copied also.


;

; *** Libraries ***

;

;

MSG_LIBS_COULD_NOT_OPEN_INTUITION_LIBRARY (1//)

Impossible d'ouvrir la librairie Intuition.         <-- Your translation here.

; Could not open Intuition library.

;

MSG_LIBS_COULD_NOT_OPEN_GRAPHICS_LIBRARY (//)

Impossible d'ouvrir la librairie Graphics.          <-- Your translation here.

; Could not open Graphics library.

;

MSG_LIBS_COULD_NOT_OPEN_DOS_LIBRARY (//)

Impossible d'ouvrir la librairie DOS.               <-- Your translation here.

; Could not open DOS library.

;



MSG_SHELLWINDOW_COULD_NOT_FIND_SHELL_WINDOW_NAMED_X (//)

Impossible de trouver la fenêtre Shell\\n\\           <-- Your translation here.

; Could not find the Shell window\\n\\

appelée \\"%s\\"\\n\\                                   <-- Your translation here.

; named \\"%s\\"\\n\\

sur l'écran public\\n\\                               <-- Your translation here.

; on the public screen\\n\\

appelé \\"%s\\".\\n\\n\\                                 <-- Your translation here.

; named \\"%s\\".\\n\\n\\

Dois-je en ouvrir une?                              <-- Your translation here.

; Should I open one?

;



If the first character is a backslash, \\, then that is notifying you that

the line is split across more than one line.  The backslash must be left as the

last character to signal Universal Translator that there are more lines to the

string.  Do not count the backslash as part of the string and be sure not to

duplicate it.



The first space between the semi-colin and the string is not part of the

string.


If there is a string like the one below:



MSG_STRING_NOT_USED_BUT_RESERVED (//)


MSG_NORMAL_STRING (//)

Normal String



then you must put "\\0" for the string or you will get an undefined string

error.


